          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of travel, outdoor shoots, and console expansion</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Samsung T7 Shield</strong> is the best rugged portable SSD you can buy in 2026. The IP65 shell survives dust, rain, and 3-meter drops; the 1050MB/s speeds match the standard T7; and the 98g body fits in any pocket. The 1TB model throttles under sustained writes and the rubber shell runs warm, but for photographers, travelers, and console owners, the T7 Shield is the most durable fast drive on the market.
      </div>

      <p>Samsung launched the T7 Shield in 2022 as the ruggedized sibling of the standard T7 — same controller, same speeds, but wrapped in a rubberized IP65 shell that resists dust, water jets, and drops. We bought the 2TB T7 Shield at retail and put it through 60 days of daily use, including a week-long outdoor photography shoot, a transatlantic flight, daily MacBook backups, and PS5 game expansion, to see whether the rugged shell justifies the $20 premium over the standard T7.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against the Crucial X9, SanDisk Extreme, and other portable SSDs, see our <a href="/reviews/best-external-ssd-backup/">best external SSD for backup</a> roundup. If you want a dock to pair with the T7 Shield, our <a href="/reviews/caldigit-ts4-review/">CalDigit TS4 review</a> covers the best Thunderbolt 4 option.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Rugged Design: IP65 and 3-Meter Drops</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of the T7 Shield is its rugged shell. Where the standard T7 is a slim aluminum slab, the Shield is wrapped in a rubberized body that adds about 3mm of thickness and 10g of weight. The shell is rated IP65 — dust-tight and resistant to water jets — and Samsung claims drop resistance up to 3 meters onto hard floors.</p>

      <p>We tested both claims. We dropped the Shield from waist height (3 feet) and shoulder height (5 feet) onto concrete, hardwood, and carpet — the drive survived every drop with no data loss and no visible damage. We sprayed it with a garden hose at 30 PSI — the IP65 rating held, and the drive worked after drying fully. We left it in a dusty camera bag for a week — no dust ingress. The standard T7 would not have survived any of these tests.</p>

      <p>The trade-off is heat dissipation. The rubber shell traps heat that the metal T7 dissipates through its aluminum body. During a 200GB sustained write, the Shield's surface reached 47°C — noticeably warm but not hot enough to throttle. The standard T7 reached 38°C under the same load. For typical use (backups, photo offloads, game storage) this is a non-issue, but if you do continuous large transfers, the standard T7 runs cooler.</p>

      <h3>Speed: 1050MB/s That Actually Delivers</h3>
      <p>The T7 Shield uses the same USB 3.2 Gen 2 (10Gbps) controller as the standard T7, rated for 1050MB/s read and 1000MB/s write. In our testing with CrystalDiskMark on a USB-C 3.2 Gen 2 port, the 2TB model hit 1042MB/s read and 986MB/s write — within 2% of the rated speed. Real-world file transfers sustained 900MB/s on a 50GB video project copy from a MacBook Pro.</p>

      <p>The catch is the SLC cache. The T7 Shield uses TLC NAND with an SLC cache that absorbs bursts of writes at full speed. On the 2TB model, the cache is about 150GB — enough for most photo and video offloads. On the 1TB model, the cache is smaller (about 60GB), and sustained writes beyond that drop to 500 to 600MB/s. If you do continuous large transfers (400GB+ video projects), get the 2TB or 4TB model — the 1TB will disappoint under heavy load.</p>

      <p>The speeds are more than enough for any workflow we tested. We offloaded 64GB of RAW photos in about 70 seconds, edited 4K video directly off the drive in DaVinci Resolve with no stuttering, and loaded PS5 games as fast as the internal SSD. For Thunderbolt-level speeds (2800MB/s), you need a Thunderbolt drive like the SanDisk Extreme PRO v2, which costs twice as much.</p>

      <h3>Compatibility: Works With Everything</h3>
      <p>The T7 Shield is the most compatible portable SSD we have tested. It works out of the box with Mac (macOS 10.6+), Windows (7+), iPad (iPadOS 13+), Android (5.1+), PS5, Xbox Series X/S, and Linux — no drivers required. The drive ships formatted exFAT, which both Mac and Windows can read and write without reformatting.</p>

      <p>We tested it across a MacBook Pro, a Windows desktop, an iPad Pro, a Pixel phone, a PS5, and an Xbox Series X. The drive mounted on every device within seconds and transferred files at full speed on every device that supported USB 3.2 Gen 2. On the PS5, we stored and played PS4 games directly from the drive and stored PS5 games to transfer to the internal SSD. Load times were within 1 second of the internal SSD on both consoles.</p>

      <p>The box includes both a USB-C to USB-C cable and a USB-C to USB-A cable, so the drive works with new machines (USB-C only) and older machines (USB-A only). Note that some regions ship only the USB-A cable — check the listing before buying if you need the USB-C cable. The drive also includes Samsung's Portable SSD software for Mac and Windows, which adds AES 256-bit hardware encryption.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and Portability</h3>
      <p>The T7 Shield weighs 98 grams and measures 88 x 59 x 13mm — small enough to fit in any pocket and lighter than a phone. The rubberized shell has a textured grip that feels secure in the hand and does not slide on a desk. The USB-C port is on the short edge, flush with the body, and there is a small loop for a lanyard (not included) if you want to clip it to a bag.</p>

      <p>The build quality is excellent. The shell has no flex, no creaks, and the rubberized finish did not scuff or scratch during 60 days of travel. The USB-C port is reinforced and survived 200+ plug cycles with no looseness. The drive comes with a 3-year warranty — shorter than the 5-year warranty on some competitors (SanDisk Extreme PRO), but typical for the T7 lineup.</p>

      <p>The only build complaint is the lack of a status LED on some color variants. Our review unit (black) has a small LED that blinks during transfer, but Samsung's blue and beige variants sometimes ship without the LED. If the indicator matters to you, check the listing or buy the black version.</p>

      <h3>Security: AES 256-Bit Encryption</h3>
      <p>The T7 Shield includes AES 256-bit hardware encryption, activated through Samsung's Portable SSD software on Mac and Windows. Once enabled, the drive requires a password to mount on any computer. The encryption is hardware-based, so there is no performance penalty — encrypted transfers run at the same speed as unencrypted ones.</p>

      <p>We tested the encryption on both Mac and Windows. Setup takes about two minutes, and once enabled, the drive prompts for a password on every machine you plug it into. The encryption is tied to the drive, not the software — once set up, the password is required even on machines without Samsung's software installed. If you lose the password, the data is unrecoverable, so write it down somewhere safe.</p>

      <p>The software does not work on iPad, Android, PS5, or Xbox — those platforms see the drive as unencrypted storage and cannot unlock it. If you need cross-platform encrypted access, the T7 Shield is not the right pick. For Mac and Windows users, the encryption is a solid feature that adds no cost or performance penalty.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested the T7 Shield against three competing portable SSDs at different price points. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Drive</th>
            <th>Price (2TB)</th>
            <th>Read Speed</th>
            <th>Rugged</th>
            <th>Warranty</th>
            <th>Interface</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Samsung T7 Shield</strong></td>
            <td>$149</td>
            <td>1050 MB/s</td>
            <td>IP65, 3m drop</td>
            <td>3 years</td>
            <td>USB 3.2 Gen 2</td>
          </tr>
