            <td>Thunderbolt 3</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Samsung T7</strong> (standard) is $20 cheaper for the same speeds, but has no rugged shell. If you use the drive only on a desk, the standard T7 is the better value. If you travel, shoot outdoors, or have ever killed a drive by dropping it, the Shield's $20 premium is worth it. See our <a href="/reviews/best-external-ssd-backup/">external SSD roundup</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Crucial X9 Pro</strong> matches the T7 Shield's speeds for $10 less and adds a 5-year warranty (vs Samsung's 3 years). It is not rugged — no IP rating, no drop resistance — but for desk-only use, the longer warranty makes it a strong pick. If ruggedness is not a priority, the X9 Pro is the better value.</p>

      <p>The <strong>SanDisk Extreme PRO v2</strong> is the Thunderbolt option — double the speed (2000MB/s) at double the price. It has a lesser IP55 rating (water jets, less dust protection) and a shorter 2m drop rating. If you need Thunderbolt speeds for video editing, the SanDisk is the pick. If USB 3.2 Gen 2 speeds are enough (and they are for almost everyone), the T7 Shield is the better value.</p>

      <p>Pair the T7 Shield with a <a href="/reviews/caldigit-ts4-review/">CalDigit TS4 dock</a> for a clean desktop setup with fast USB-C ports, or a <a href="/reviews/best-usb-c-hub-macbook/">USB-C hub</a> if you need more ports on a laptop.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the T7 Shield if you travel, shoot outdoors, or have ever killed a portable SSD by dropping it. The IP65 shell and 3-meter drop resistance are worth the $20 premium over the standard T7 for anyone who moves the drive off a desk.</p>

      <p>Get the 2TB or 4TB model if you do sustained large transfers. The 1TB model's smaller SLC cache throttles writes to 500 to 600MB/s after about 60GB. The 2TB model sustains full speed for 150GB — enough for almost any photo or video project. The price-per-GB is also better on the larger capacities.</p>

      <p>Skip the T7 Shield and get the standard T7 if you only use the drive on a desk. The rugged shell adds heat, weight, and $20 for no benefit if the drive never leaves your desk. The standard T7 runs cooler and costs less for identical speeds.</p>

      <p>Consider the Crucial X9 Pro instead if you want a longer warranty and do not need ruggedness. The X9 Pro costs $10 less, matches the T7 Shield's speeds, and ships with a 5-year warranty. The trade-off is no IP rating and no drop resistance.</p>

      <p>Buy from an authorized retailer (Amazon, Best Buy, Samsung directly) to ensure the full 3-year warranty. Gray-market drives often ship without cables or warranty coverage. Check the listing for the included cables — some regions ship only the USB-A cable, and you may need to buy a USB-C cable separately.</p>

      <p>Avoid the 500GB model unless you only need it for documents. The 500GB T7 Shield has the smallest SLC cache and the worst sustained-write performance in the lineup. Spend $30 more for the 1TB, or $60 more for the 2TB — the price-per-GB improves dramatically at higher capacities.</p>

